		<section><title>setting-ldap options</title><table>
			<tgroup cols="2">
					<colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1*"/>
					<colspec colname="col2" colwidth="3*"/>
					<thead>
						<row>
							<entry>setting-ldap options</entry>
							<entry>Description</entry>
						</row>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<row>
							<entry>--ldap-admins=</entry>
							<entry>Setting up a full LDAP administrator.</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>--ldap-roadmins=</entry>
							<entry>Setting up a read-only LDAP administrator.</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>--ldap-enable=[0|1]</entry>
							<entry>Enables the LDAP protocol for authentication.</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>--ldap-default=[admin | roadmins | none]</entry>
							<entry>Sets the default LDAP accounts.</entry>
						</row>
					</tbody>
				</tgroup>
		</table>
		<p>Example:
				<codeblock>--cluster=localhost -u Administrator -p password --ldap-enable=1 
--ldap-roadmins=userD,bjones02 --ldap-admins=userJ,bjones01 --ldap-default=none</codeblock></p>
			<p>If you run the above command, it will add administrators to LDAP in the following way: userD
				plus bjones02 as read-only administrators,  and userJ plus bjones01as full
				administrators. Commas between user names are converted automatically to new
				lines.</p>
		
		
		
